Identity. Users versus service accounts.

Two kinds of identity exist in a cluster, and they are easy to mix up.

First, users, which are for humans, and for continuous integration systems. A user is whatever the ay-pee-eye server figures out from your kube config. A client certificate's subject, giving a user and a group. An open eye-dee connect token's subject claim. A static token. Or a webhook response. And here is the key point. Users are not kubernetes objects. There is no kubectl create user. The ay-pee-eye server does not store them, it just recognises the identities your authenticator chain returns. You add a user by issuing a new client certificate, signed by the cluster authority, or by configuring an open eye-dee connect provider.

Second, service accounts, which are for pods. A service account is a real kubernetes object, namespaced, living in the ay-pee-eye server. A pod references it by name, the kube-let mounts a token for it, and the pod uses that token to call the ay-pee-eye server. So users authenticate people. Service accounts authenticate workloads. And are-back applies to either.

On the token. The kube-let mounts three files into the pod, the certificate authority, the namespace, and the token. Modern tokens are bound. They expire after about an hour, and are auto rotated, scoped to specific audiences, and revoked when the pod dies. Legacy, never expiring secret tokens are phased out, and should be treated as suspicious past kubernetes one point twenty-four.

A few best practices. The default service account has zero permissions, so make a workload specific one, and do not grant the default more than it needs. Set auto mount service account token to false, for pods that never call the ay-pee-eye server. And beware the group system authenticated, which includes everyone. A cluster role binding to it grants all. On our map, this is the service account chip in the are-back box. The identity a pod carries into the ay-pee-eye server.
